# arvo-storage. Design

The minimal bare-primitive layer of arvo. Sits at the bottom of every
dependency chain in the substrate. Hosts the only fielded primitive
types whose existence requires wrapping bare Rust primitives directly,
the strategy markers used by every numeric type, and the typed
meta-bit newtypes that carry bit-count meta values through const
generic positions. `#![no_std]`, no alloc.

Depends on `arvo-transparent` (for the `Transparent` const unsafe
trait that every `repr(transparent)` type implements) and
`arvo-strategy` (for the strategy markers and `UContainerFor<N>` /
`IContainerFor<N>` projections). No other workspace dependencies.

This crate is small on purpose. Everything else in the arvo stack
(bit-level contracts, mask types, narrowing, fixed-point arithmetic,
algorithms) lives upstream and consumes these primitives via trait
bounds. New types here are added only when the type genuinely cannot
be expressed without wrapping a bare primitive.

## Bits

`Bits<const N: u8, S: Strategy = Hot, Sign: Signedness = Unsigned>` is
the N-bit storage primitive. A `#[repr(transparent)]` newtype over
`<S as BitsContainerFor<N, Sign>>::T`. The container projection picks
the bare primitive (or `MultiContainer<HiT, LoT>` at the wider widths)
that holds N bits under strategy S and signedness Sign. `Bits<8, Hot>`
lowers to `u8`, `Bits<7, Hot>` lowers to `u8` (with the high bit unused
under Hot), `Bits<32, Warm>` lowers to `u32`, `Bits<64, Hot>` to `u64`,
`Bits<96, Hot>` to `u128`, `Bits<200, Hot>` to a strategy-driven
`MultiContainer` shape, and so on per the strategy bands.

Default `Sign = Unsigned` keeps every existing `Bits<N, S>` call site
unchanged. Domain code that wants signed bit patterns writes
`Bits<N, S, Signed>` directly; in practice the consumer reaches for
`IFixed<I, F, S>` instead, which is itself `repr(transparent)` over
`Bits<{1+I+F}, S, Signed>` (the symmetric counterpart of UFixed's
wrap of `Bits<{I+F}, S, Unsigned>`).

The public surface is partitioned and minimal:

```rust
impl<const N: u8, S: Strategy, Sign: Signedness> Bits<N, S, Sign>
where S: BitsContainerFor<N, Sign>,
{
    pub const fn from_raw(raw: <S as BitsContainerFor<N, Sign>>::T) -> Self;
    pub const fn to_raw(self) -> <S as BitsContainerFor<N, Sign>>::T;
}
```

Plus `Deref<Target = ::T>`, `AsRef<::T>`, and `impl const Transparent`.

Per round 202604271346 D-7, every per-size helper is gone. No
`from_raw_uN` / `to_raw_uN` family. No `From<uN>` per N. No
`Bits::new(u64)` / `Bits::bits()` deprecated front-doors. The
`impl_bits_uN` macro family is removed in its entirety.

Consumers that need to take a wider raw value and narrow it to fit
`Bits<N, S, Sign>` go through `Narrow<T>::narrow_to::<N>` from
`arvo-bits-contracts` (post-merge of arvo-narrow-contracts during
round 202604280034). The `Narrow` impls compose `Mask<W>`,
`BitLogic`, and the `as` operator to produce the typed container
output. The pipeline is explicit at the call site instead of hidden
inside per-size helpers.

## Strategy markers

`Hot`, `Warm`, `Cold`, `Precise`. Zero-sized types. Each implements
the sealed `Strategy` marker trait declared in `arvo-strategy`. Each
derives `ConstParamTy` so it works as a const generic argument.

Strategy semantics are unchanged from prior rounds. `Hot` picks the
narrowest container for the bit width (1..=8 bits use `u8`, 9..=16
use `u16`, 17..=32 use `u32`, 33..=64 use `u64`). `Warm` picks the
ergonomic container (always at least `u32` for `N <= 32`, `u64` for
33..=64). `Cold` is reserved for bitpacked storage of N > 64 (out of
scope this round). `Precise` uses arbitrary-width carriers (`u64`
within this round's scope).

The `UContainerFor<N>` and `IContainerFor<N>` per-N impls live in
`arvo-strategy`, not here. They project `S + N` to the bare primitive
container (or to `MultiContainer<HiT, LoT>` at the wider widths). The
`BitsContainerFor<N, Sign>` indirection trait (also in `arvo-strategy`)
selects between U and I tables based on the Sign axis.

## Signedness markers

`Unsigned` and `Signed` are zero-sized markers. Each implements the
sealed `Signedness` marker trait and derives `ConstParamTy` so it
appears as a const-generic argument on `Bits<N, S, Sign>`.

```rust
pub const trait Signedness: sealed::Sealed + Copy + Clone + Default + 'static {}

#[derive(ConstParamTy, PartialEq, Eq, Copy, Clone, Debug, Default)]
pub struct Unsigned;

#[derive(ConstParamTy, PartialEq, Eq, Copy, Clone, Debug, Default)]
pub struct Signed;

impl const Signedness for Unsigned {}
impl const Signedness for Signed {}
```

The Sign axis on `Bits` was introduced in round 202604280500 to close
the symmetry gap between UFixed and IFixed. Default `Sign = Unsigned`
on `Bits` keeps existing call sites unchanged; IFixed's
`repr(transparent)` wrap of `Bits<{1+I+F}, S, Signed>` reaches for the
non-default value.

## MultiContainer

`pub struct MultiContainer<HiT, LoT>` is the multi-value storage
primitive used at logical bit widths above any single native primitive
(beyond `u128` / `i128`). Generic over two `BitPrim` components: the
hi half and the lo half.

```rust
#[repr(C)]
pub struct MultiContainer<HiT: BitPrim, LoT: BitPrim> {
    pub hi: HiT,
    pub lo: LoT,
}
```

The `BitPrim` sealed trait abstracts the native primitives that can
participate in a multi-container split: `u8`, `u16`, `u32`, `u64`,
`u128`, `i8`, `i16`, `i32`, `i64`, `i128`. Trait declarations in
`arvo-strategy` so the dispatch tables there stay self-contained.

Strategy projection picks the (HiT, LoT) shape per the four canonical
strategies' policies (smallest-footprint vs same-length doubled). The
per-cell tabulation lives in `arvo-strategy/DESIGN.md.tmpl`.

Round 202604280500 ships the storage shape only. Arithmetic on
multi-value containers (`UArith` / `IArith` dispatch on `MultiContainer`,
`UWidenFrom` / `UNarrowFrom` cross-container widening) is BACKLOG-tracked
for a follow-up round; UFixed / IFixed at 129..=256 logical width await
that arith bridge before they compile (their cap stays at 128 in this
round). `Bits<129..=256, S, Sign>` is available standalone with its
storage projection landing in this round.

## Bool

`pub struct Bool(pub bool)`. The newtype that carries Rust's `bool`
through the substrate's "every public type is an arvo wrapper" rule.
Used by predicates (`is_zero`, `bit`, `Predicate` family) and in
control flow that returns to consumer code.

`Bool` implements `Try` with `Residual = Infallible` so the `?`
operator extracts the inner `bool` for use in `if` expressions. The
extraction has zero runtime cost (the Continue path is the only
inhabited path).

`Bool` implements the const unsafe `Transparent` trait so the inner
`bool` is reachable in const context via `arvo::raw(b)`.

## USize

`pub struct USize(pub usize)`. The newtype for platform-pointer-width
unsigned integers. Used as the universal index/length type across the
substrate: `Cap<N>` wraps it, `HasBitWidth::WIDTH` returns it, every
arvo-tensor offset is a `USize`.

This round preserves `USize`'s field shape (still `usize`). Future
rounds may migrate the inner field to `Bits<{cfg-platform-width},
Hot>` for a unified bit-storage view; the prior round explored that
direction and parked it.

`USize` implements the const unsafe `Transparent` trait.

## Typed meta-bit newtypes

Three `#[repr(transparent)]` newtypes over `Bits<9, Hot>`. Each
derives `ConstParamTy` (via `feature(const_param_ty_trait)` plus a
manual `ConstParamTy_` impl on `Bits<N, S, Sign>`):

```rust
#[derive(ConstParamTy, ...)]
#[repr(transparent)]
pub struct IBits(pub Bits<9, Hot>);

#[derive(ConstParamTy, ...)]
#[repr(transparent)]
pub struct FBits(pub Bits<9, Hot>);

#[derive(ConstParamTy, ...)]
#[repr(transparent)]
pub struct Width(pub Bits<9, Hot>);
```

`IBits` carries the integer-bit count of a fixed-point type. `FBits`
carries the fractional-bit count. `Width` carries an arbitrary
bit-width meta value (used by `Bits<const N: u8, S, Sign>` consumers
that want a typed parameter, by `Hasher<const W: Width>`, and by mask
consumers that want a typed width parameter).

The carrier widened from `Bits<7, Hot>` (range 0..=127) to
`Bits<9, Hot>` (range 0..=511 native; 0..=256 used) in round
202604280500. The substrate's logical-width cap rises from 128 to 256;
9 bits is the minimum carrier covering `0..=256` without offset
trickery. One bit is wasted at the const-generic-position layer
(values 257..=511 are valid bit patterns but unused at the meta-newtype
layer). Per the `arvo-toolbox-not-policer` workspace rule, honest
range trumps offset packing; the wasted bit costs nothing at codegen.

The Q-A spike (rustc 1.96.0-nightly fda6d37bb 2026-03-27, four
nightly features active) confirmed the projection cascade resolves
under const trait dispatch. `ibits(7)` works in const context.
`Carrier<{ ibits(7) }>` works as a const generic argument. The
projection `<Hot as UContainerFor<9>>::T` resolves to `u16` at compile
time.

## Const-fn helpers

Three small const fns make the typed meta-bit newtypes ergonomic at
literal call sites:

```rust
pub const fn ibits(n: u16) -> IBits;
pub const fn fbits(n: u16) -> FBits;
pub const fn width(n: u16) -> Width;
```

These are the only positions in the crate where a bare integer
appears in function-parameter form. The parameter type widened from
`u8` to `u16` in round 202604280500 alongside the carrier widening
(`<Hot as UContainerFor<9>>::T = u16`). They exist so consumers can
write `UFixed<{ ibits(13) }, { fbits(3) }, Warm>` instead of
construction boilerplate; literal-style call sites (`ibits(13)`)
continue to work via `u16` inference at the argument position. The
bare `u16` parameter is the documented exception under the workspace
no-bare-primitives rule (definition-site exception category 4).

## What does NOT live here

- Trait declarations (live in the contract crates: `arvo-transparent`,
  `arvo-strategy`, `arvo-bits-contracts` (which now also hosts
  `Narrow<T>` post-merge), `arvo-mask-contracts`,
  `arvo-numeric-contracts`).
- Trait impls (live in the implementation crates: `arvo-bits`,
  `arvo-bitmask`, `arvo-narrow`, `arvo-tensor`, `arvo-hash`).
- Compositions over `Bits` (`UFixed`, `IFixed`, `FastFloat`,
  `StrictFloat`) live in the `arvo` facade. `UFixed` is a
  `repr(transparent)` newtype over `Bits<{I+F}, S, Unsigned>` (default
  Sign omitted at the call site). `IFixed` is a `repr(transparent)`
  newtype over `Bits<{1+I+F}, S, Signed>`, the symmetric counterpart
  shipped in round 202604280500.
- Algorithms (live in `arvo-graph`, `arvo-sparse`, `arvo-comb`,
  `arvo-spectral`).
- Aliases and re-exports (live in the `arvo` facade).

## Sign axis on Bits (shipped round 202604280500)

The Sign axis on `Bits<N, S, Sign>` shipped in round 202604280500.
See `## Bits` and `## Signedness markers` above for the declarative
content; the previous "Coming in a follow-up round" placeholder is
gone. IFixed's symmetric reshape over `Bits<{1+I+F}, S, Signed>` lands
in the same round.

